05426nam a22010215i 9780520930285DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20012001cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021696392  a97805209302857 a10.1525/97805209302852doi  a(DE-B1597)519089  a(OCoLC)777466415  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aF912.L57 4aF912 .L57 F73 2003 7aNAT0100002bisacsh04a979.821 aFradkin, Philip L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWildest Alaska :bJourneys of Great Peril in Lituya Bay /cPhilip L. Fradkin. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (197 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPROLOGUE -- tI. BEGINNINGS -- tII. THE PLACE -- tIII. THE TLINGITS -- tIV. THE FRENCH -- tV. THE RUSSIANS -- tVI. THE AMERICANS -- tVII. THE WAVE -- tVIII. THE PRESENTS153 -- tIX. TOMALES BAY -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tSOURCES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTwenty-five years ago Philip L. Fradkin read a book about a remote bay on the Gulf of Alaska coast. The noted environmental historian was attracted by the threads of violence woven through the natural and human histories of Lituya Bay. Could these histories be related, and if so, how? The attempt to define the power of this wild place was a tantalizing and, as it turned out, dangerous quest. This compelling and eerie memoir tells of Fradkin's odyssey through recorded human history and eventually to the bay itself, as he explores the dark and unyielding side of nature.Natural forces have always dominated Lituya Bay. Immense storms, powerful earthquakes, huge landslides, and giant waves higher than the world's tallest skyscrapers pound the whale-shaped fjord. Compelling for its deadly beauty, the bay has attracted visitors over time, but it has never been mastered by them.Its seasonal occupants throughout recorded history—Tlingit Indians, European explorers, gold miners, and coastal fishermen seeking a harbor of refuge—have drowned, gone mad, slaughtered fur-bearing animals with abandon, sifted the black sand beaches for minute particles of gold, and murdered each other. Only a hermit found peace there. Then the author and his small son visited the bay and were haunted by a grizzly bear.As an environmental writer for the Los Angeles Times and western editor of Audubon magazine, Fradkin has traveled from Tierra del Fuego to the North Slope of Alaska. But nothing prepared him for Lituya Bay, a place so powerful it turned one person's hair white. This story resonates with echoes of Melville, Poe, and Conrad as it weaves together the human and natural histories of a beautiful and wild place.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNatural disasterszAlaskazLituya Bay RegionxHistory. 0aNatural disasterszAlaskazLituya BayxHistory. 0aNatural disasterszAlaska. 0aNatural historyzAlaskazLituya Bay Region. 0aNatural historyzAlaskazLituya Bay. 0aNatural historyzAlaska. 0aViolencezAlaskazLituya Bay RegionxHistory. 0aViolencezAlaskazLituya BayxHistory. 0aViolencezAlaska. 7aNATURE / Ecology.2bisacsh  aalaska.  aanimals.  acoastal.  aenvironmental history.  aenvironmental.  aexplorers.  afishing.  afjords.  agold mining.  agulf of alaska.  ahistorian.  ahuman history.  aindians.  aindigenous people.  alituya bay.  amemoir.  anatural features.  anatural history.  anatural world.  anature.  anorthern united states.  asettlers.  asmall town.  atourism.  atourists.  atrue story.  aviolence.  avisitors.  awestern united states.  aworld history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversit